#let images = (
  "22.1": (
    caption: [Stages of maize embryogenesis showing the developmental progression from zygotic stage through maturation. (A) Zygotic stage: single-cell stage after fertilization. (B) Globular stage: spherical embryo with basic cell differentiation. (C) Coleoptile stage: marked by formation of distinct coleoptile and scutellum. (D) Leaf primordia stage: emergence of first leaf structures. (E) Maturation stage: fully developed embryo ready for dormancy. Longitudinal sections demonstrate the stereotyped pattern of cell divisions and tissue differentiation characteristic of monocot embryogenesis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.2": (
    caption: [The stages of Arabidopsis embryogenesis characterized by precise, predictable patterns of cell division. (A) One-cell embryo after asymmetric zygotic division forming apical and basal cells. (B) Two-cell embryo with distinct cell fates. (C) Eight-cell embryo showing upper and lower tiers. (D) Mid-globular stage with distinct protoderm surface layer. (E) Early heart stage with emerging cotyledon primordia. (F) Late heart stage showing bilateral symmetry. (G) Torpedo stage with elongated hypocotyl. (H) Mature embryo with all major tissues differentiated. This sequence illustrates the establishment of apical-basal polarity and radial tissue patterning in eudicots.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.3": (
    caption: [The seedling is organized along two perpendicular axes that define plant body architecture. Longitudinal cross section (left) shows the apical-basal axis extending from the shoot apex to the root tip, establishing primary growth direction. Transverse cross section (right) displays the radial axis extending from the central vascular cylinder outward through ground tissue to the epidermis. These two axes are established during embryogenesis and maintained throughout plant development, forming the fundamental organizational framework for all plant organs.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.4": (
    caption: [Pattern formation during Arabidopsis embryogenesis showing cell lineage contributions to seedling structures. Clonally related cell groups (descended from common progenitors) are indicated by distinct colors. Following asymmetric zygotic division, the apical cell produces an eight-cell embryo with two tiers of four cells each. The upper tier generates the shoot apical meristem and most cotyledon primordia. The lower tier forms the hypocotyl, portions of cotyledons, embryonic root, and upper cells of the root apical meristem. The basal cell produces a suspensor connecting the embryo to maternal tissue. This demonstrates how position-dependent mechanisms determine cell fate during embryonic development.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.5": (
    caption: [Live-cell imaging of cytoskeletal dynamics during early Arabidopsis embryo development revealing the establishment of polarity. (A) Schematic diagram of zygote development within the ovary. (B) Time-lapse fluorescence microscopy series from egg cell through first zygotic division. Green fluorescence marks microtubules; magenta shows surrounding ovule autofluorescence. Following fertilization, the zygote shrinks and cortical microtubules become randomly oriented. The zygote then bulges apically where transverse microtubule rings form. This bulge develops into the apical cell while the base becomes the basal cell. Microtubule reorganization precedes and directs the asymmetric cell division that establishes apical-basal polarity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.6": (
    caption: [Periclinal and anticlinal cell divisions establish tissue layers and cell numbers within layers. Periclinal divisions produce new cell walls parallel to the tissue surface, contributing to establishment of new tissue layers (such as protoderm formation). Anticlinal divisions produce cell walls perpendicular to the tissue surface, increasing cell numbers within existing layers without changing layer number. The balance and regulation of these two division planes is critical for proper radial patterning and tissue organization during embryogenesis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.7": (
    caption: [Orientation of cell divisions in the Arabidopsis embryo can follow different patterns with distinct outcomes. Four cells of an eight-cell embryo are shown at top. Each cell can divide symmetrically anticlinally through the cell center (bottom right), following the minimum surface area rule and generating two equal-volume daughter cells. Alternatively, under regulatory control such as by auxin signaling, cells can divide asymmetrically periclinally (bottom left), deviating from the minimum surface area rule to generate distinct outer and inner cell layers. This demonstrates how chemical signals override geometric constraints to establish proper tissue patterning.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.8": (
    caption: [Fates of specific embryonic cells are not rigidly determined by lineage but rather by position-dependent signals. This clonal analysis tracks individual cell descendants using a GUS reporter system activated by random transposon excision. Seedlings are sorted into categories (A-F) according to positions and extents of GUS-expressing sectors. Each sector arose from a single marked cell in the young embryo. The variable positions of marked cell descendants in different organs demonstrate that cell fate is determined by cellular position and signaling environment rather than strict lineage, supporting the importance of position-dependent mechanisms in plant development.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.9": (
    caption: [Extra cell divisions do not block establishment of basic radial pattern elements, demonstrating the robustness of position-dependent patterning. Arabidopsis fass mutants cannot form preprophase microtubule bands and show highly irregular cell division and expansion planes, resulting in severe deformation. Despite these abnormalities, mutants still produce recognizable tissues and organs in correct positions. Comparison of wild-type (A-C) and fass mutant (D-F) embryos, seedlings, and root cross sections shows that although organs are abnormal, radially oriented tissue patterns persist. This indicates that positional information, not precise cell division patterns, primarily governs tissue identity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.10": (
    caption: [The potential for intercellular protein movement changes during embryo development, affecting cell-to-cell communication. Small (B,H,N), intermediate (C,I,O), and large (D,J,P) GFP reporter proteins show different distribution patterns in embryos of increasing age (early heart, late heart, mid-torpedo stages). All constructs use STM promoter producing transcripts in restricted regions. Small proteins move readily at all stages, but larger protein mobility decreases and becomes more restricted in older embryos. This developmental regulation of plasmodesmatal permeability controls which signaling molecules can move between cells, thereby influencing pattern formation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.11": (
    caption: [Representative embryo lethal Arabidopsis mutants demonstrate genes essential for embryo viability and development. Each panel shows the arrested developmental stage of the indicated mutant. HSN4 is involved in histidine biosynthesis; TTN10 participates in mitotic DNA replication initiation; EMB3001 contributes to proteolysis pathways. These mutants arrest at various embryonic stages and cannot progress to maturity, indicating that their corresponding genes are essential for embryogenesis. Such mutants reveal fundamental cellular processes required for embryo development.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.12": (
    caption: [Genes essential for Arabidopsis embryogenesis identified from seedling defective mutant phenotypes, revealing specific developmental functions. Wild-type seedlings are contrasted with mutants at comparable stages. (A) GNOM gene establishes apical-basal polarity; gnom mutants show disordered embryo organization. (B) MONOPTEROS gene is necessary for basal patterning and primary root formation; monopteros mutants have hypocotyl, shoot apical meristem, and cotyledons but lack primary root. (C) Schematic of four deletion mutant types showing specific missing regions: each mutant lacks specific embryonic domains present in wild type, demonstrating that different genes control development of distinct embryo regions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.13": (
    caption: [PIN1-dependent auxin movement during early embryogenesis establishes hormone gradients that direct pattern formation. Auxin movement, inferred from asymmetric PIN1 protein distribution and DR5 auxin-responsive reporter activity, is depicted by arrows. Blue areas denote cells with maximum auxin concentrations; brown shading indicates vascular cylinder. Auxin maxima resulting from local hormone synthesis create gradients that are reinforced and maintained by polar PIN1 orientation in cell membranes. This demonstrates how auxin acts as a mobile morphogenic signal, with directional transport creating concentration gradients that specify cell fates and guide tissue patterning.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.14": (
    caption: [Evidence for auxin's role in embryonic development through comparison of wild-type and mutant phenotypes. (A) Wild-type Arabidopsis embryo showing normal cotyledon separation and bilateral symmetry. (B) pin1-1 mutant embryo displaying failure in cotyledon separation. The pin1 mutation disrupts auxin transport by eliminating a key efflux carrier protein. Chemical inhibition of auxin transport in vitro produces similar phenotypes. These results demonstrate that proper auxin transport and gradient formation are essential for establishing correct embryonic pattern, particularly for cotyledon initiation and separation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.15": (
    caption: [Summary of the sequence of radial patterning events during Arabidopsis embryogenesis showing progressive tissue layer formation. Five successive embryonic stages in longitudinal section illustrate the origin of distinct tissue types, from protoderm delineation (left) through vascular tissue formation (right). The number of tissue layers increases through action of initial cells that undergo regulated periclinal divisions. Cross-sectional view of late heart stage basal portion (far right) shows radial organization of tissues. This sequence demonstrates how radial patterning progressively subdivides the embryo into concentric tissue layers with distinct identities: epidermis, cortex, endodermis, and vascular tissues.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.16": (
    caption: [ATML1 and PDF2 genes are required for establishment of normal epidermis with proper cell identity and function. Comparison of wild-type plant (A) and double atml1/pdf2 mutant (B) reveals that mutant superficial layers resemble mesophyll rather than epidermis. The partially exposed mesophyll in wild type (A) contrasts with the mutant's lack of distinct epidermal characteristics. These transcription factors are essential for specifying epidermal cell fate during embryogenesis. Without proper ATML1 and PDF2 function, outer layer cells fail to acquire epidermal identity and instead adopt ground tissue characteristics.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.17": (
    caption: [The cytokinin receptor encoded by the Arabidopsis WOODEN LEG (WOL) gene is required for normal phloem development through regulation of vascular cell divisions. Comparison of wild-type (A) and wol mutant (B) roots shows absence of phloem elements in mutants, accompanied by decreased cell layer numbers. WOL (also called CYTOKININ RESPONSE 1) encodes a cytokinin receptor, implicating this hormone in radial pattern establishment. The wol mutant fails to undergo a critical cell division that normally produces xylem and phloem precursors, resulting in vascular tissue containing xylem but lacking phloem. This demonstrates cytokinin's essential role in vascular tissue differentiation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.18": (
    caption: [TMO5 and LHW transcription factors control the number of xylem and phloem cell files in all dimensions of the Arabidopsis root vascular system. (A,B) Cross sections of mature wild-type (A) and tmo5/tmo5-like1 double mutant (B) embryos show reduced vascular tissue (inside dashed lines) in mutants. (C,D) Root meristem cross sections show mutants have fewer vascular cells and phloem poles (arrows) compared to wild type; surrounding endodermal cells marked with asterisks. (E-G) Root meristems of wild type (E), TMO5 overexpression (F), and TMO5/LHW double overexpression (G) lines demonstrate that combined overexpression increases vascular cell file numbers. These transcription factors act together to regulate vascular proliferation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.19": (
    caption: [Comparison of normal and mutant radial root patterns reveals spatially defined functions of specific genes in tissue layer formation. (A) Wild-type root showing normal radial organization with distinct epidermis, cortex, endodermis, and vascular tissues arranged concentrically. (B) Defective radial root patterns of three Arabidopsis mutants: wooden leg (wol) lacks phloem, scarecrow (scr) lacks cortex layer, and short root (shr) has disrupted ground tissue organization. Each mutant specifically affects development of particular tissue layers while leaving others intact, demonstrating that distinct genetic programs control formation of each radial tissue layer.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.20": (
    caption: [The SHORT ROOT (SHR) and SCARECROW (SCR) genes control tissue patterning during root development through cell-to-cell movement and transcriptional regulation. Confocal laser scanning microscopy localizes SHR and SCR mRNAs and proteins. (A,B) SHR expression: (A) SHR promoter activity is restricted to stele (visualized by SHR promoter-GFP fusion). (B) SHR protein localizes to both central stele and adjacent endodermal nuclei (SHR promoter + coding region + GFP fusion), demonstrating protein movement from its synthesis site. (C,D) SCR expression (SCR promoter-GFP fusion): (C) In wild-type roots, SCR is transcribed in quiescent center, endodermis, and cortical-endodermal initials. (D) In shr mutants, SCR expression is abolished, showing SHR regulates SCR. This demonstrates how mobile transcription factors coordinate radial patterning.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.21": (
    caption: [Model for specification of cell identity in the root through sequential gene expression and regulatory interactions. (A) Early auxin-dependent expression of MONOPTEROS (MP) and NONPHOTOTROPIC HYPOCOTYL 4 (NPH4) genes in basal domain. (B) MP and NPH4 promote PLETHORA (PLT) expression. (C) PLT induces SCARECROW (SCR) and SHORT ROOT (SHR) expression. The combination of PLT, SCR, and SHR directs centrally positioned cells to become the quiescent center and induces WOX5 expression, which maintains surrounding initial cells (dashed line area). This cascade shows how auxin initiates a regulatory network that progressively specifies distinct cell types and establishes the root apical meristem organization.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.22": (
    caption: [Initiation of shoot and root apical meristems in the Arabidopsis embryo through mutually inhibitory transcription factor interactions. (A) Model showing regulatory control in 16-cell embryo (three-dimensional cross section with color-coded cell types). Upper tier gives rise to shoot domain; lower tier to root domain. Central to the model is mutually inhibitory interaction between HD-Zip III (top tier) and PLT (lower tier) transcription factors. PLT expression is also controlled by BODENLOS (BDL) and TOPLESS (TPL). MicroRNA miR165/166 from lower tier restricts HD-Zip III mRNA accumulation to top tier. HD-ZIP III promotes shoot initiation; PLT promotes root initiation. (B,C) Ectopic expression experiments: (B) PLT overexpression in shoot produces root meristems with statoliths. (C) HD-Zip III overexpression in lower tier creates second shoot domain. This demonstrates how mutual antagonism between transcription factors establishes opposite meristem identities.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "22.23": (
    caption: [Diverse sources of plant embryos demonstrating developmental plasticity and totipotency of plant cells. In addition to zygotes (center), many different cell types can initiate embryogenesis under appropriate conditions. Sources shown include: somatic cells within ovules (apomixis - asexual seed formation), suspensor cells (can replace damaged embryo proper), microspores (pollen precursors under stress), and cultured somatic cells (callus-derived embryos through hormone treatment). These alternative pathways produce embryos often morphologically indistinguishable from zygotic embryos. This remarkable plasticity demonstrates that embryogenic potential is not restricted to zygotes but rather can be activated in diverse cell types given appropriate developmental signals or environmental triggers.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  )
)
